<subSubSection pageId="12" pageNumber="49" type="diagnostic characters">
<paragraph pageId="12" pageNumber="49">Diagnostic characters.</paragraph>
<paragraph pageId="12" pageNumber="49">
Most similar to 
<taxonomicName authority="Martinsson &amp; Kjaerandsen, 2012" authorityName="Martinsson &amp; Kjaerandsen" authorityYear="2012" class="Insecta" family="Mycetophilidae" genus="Katatopygia" higherTaxonomySource="GBIF" kingdom="Animalia" lsidName="Katatopygia antica" order="Diptera" pageId="12" pageNumber="49" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="antica">Katatopygia antica</taxonomicName>
and 
<taxonomicName authority="Martinsson &amp; Kjaerandsen, 2012" authorityName="Martinsson &amp; Kjaerandsen" authorityYear="2012" class="Insecta" family="Mycetophilidae" genus="Katatopygia" higherTaxonomySource="GBIF" kingdom="Animalia" lsidName="Katatopygia antoma" order="Diptera" pageId="12" pageNumber="49" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="antoma">Katatopygia antoma</taxonomicName>
from which it can be separated on coloration and details of the male terminalia. Zaitzev &amp; Polevoi (2002) used four key characters to distinguish it from 
<taxonomicName authority="Martinsson &amp; Kjaerandsen, 2012" authorityName="Martinsson &amp; Kjaerandsen" authorityYear="2012" class="Insecta" family="Mycetophilidae" genus="Katatopygia" higherTaxonomySource="GBIF" kingdom="Animalia" lsidName="Katatopygia erythropyga" order="Diptera" pageId="12" pageNumber="49" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="erythropyga">Katatopygia erythropyga</taxonomicName>
: 1) absence of the apical process of the male gonostylus; 2) longer stem of M-fork; 3) scape of antenna brown; 4) abdomen uniformly brown.
</paragraph>
</subSubSection>
<subSubSection pageId="12" pageNumber="49" type="distribution">
<paragraph pageId="12" pageNumber="49">Distribution.</paragraph>
<paragraph pageId="12" pageNumber="49">The species is known only from the Yamal peninsula north in West Siberia.</paragraph>
</subSubSection>
<subSubSection pageId="12" pageNumber="49" type="remarks">
<paragraph pageId="12" pageNumber="49">Remarks.</paragraph>
<paragraph pageId="12" pageNumber="49">
The absence of the apical process of the male gonostylus is unique among the known species of 
<taxonomicName authority="Martinsson &amp; Kjaerandsen, 2012" authorityName="Martinsson &amp; Kjaerandsen" authorityYear="2012" class="Insecta" family="Mycetophilidae" genus="Katatopygia" higherTaxonomySource="GBIF" kingdom="Animalia" lsidName="Katatopygia" order="Diptera" pageId="12" pageNumber="49" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="genus">Katatopygia</taxonomicName>
and may be regarded as a secondary reduction (see discussion of phylogeny).
</paragraph>
</subSubSection>
<subSubSection pageId="12" pageNumber="49" type="type material">
<paragraph pageId="12" pageNumber="49">Type material.</paragraph>
<paragraph pageId="12" pageNumber="49">The holotype is deposited in the A.N. Severtzov Institute of Ecology and Evolution in Moscow, Russia - not studied.</paragraph>
</subSubSection>
